He argued that legality does not confer legitimacy, that a law violating natural rights is void regardless of what Parliament enacted. The power to search everyone, he warned, is the power to control everyone. General warrants place "the liberty of every man in the hands of every petty officer."

John Adams, then a young lawyer watching from the gallery, later wrote: "Then and there the child Independence was born."

What Texas did is the Writ of Assistance perfected for the digital age.

The Crown's agents had to knock on doors. Texas surrendered the data with a keystroke. The Crown's writs covered a port, a town. This covers a state of 18 million. The customs officer had to be present at the search. The DOJ need never leave Washington.

Otis argued that a man's house is his castle. Texas has made every citizen's identity a searchable file. The castle has no walls. The door has no lock. The petty officer need not even rise from his chair.

The Department of Justice claims authority under the National Voter Registration Act to obtain voter records for "roll maintenance." Even if one accepts that the NVRA permits limited federal access, it does not follow that it authorizes bulk transfer of sensitive identifiers without process, limitation, or oversight.

A statute enacted to expand voting access was never meant to justify mass federal collection of personal data on every registered voter in a state.

More importantly, legality is not the standard that matters here.

The founders did not rebel against illegal acts. The Stamp Act was legal. The Quartering Act was legal. The Writs of Assistance were legal under British law.

They were rejected anyway.

Otis understood what Texas has forgotten: authority without right is tyranny with paperwork. You can wave a statute while betraying a principle. The question is not whether the law permits. The question is whether justice allows.

The Fourth Amendment exists precisely to prohibit suspicionless, population wide data seizures. What Texas enabled is the modern functional equivalent of a general warrant: mass transfer of personal information without individualized cause, justified by nothing more than trust in whoever currently holds power.

Trust is not a limiting principle.

States administer elections. States hold voter data. That separation was meant to be a safeguard.

Twenty three states understood this and said no. They are now defending that principle in court.

Texas chose alignment over protection. It converted federalism from a shield into a favor. It decided that cooperation with this administration mattered more than insulating its citizens from federal surveillance.

Data given to allies today is infrastructure available to adversaries tomorrow. Texas didn't just trust this administration, it abandoned the principle that sensitive voter data should not flow to federal law enforcement on demand.

That principle exists precisely because power changes hands.

There is a word for officials who surrender the rights of their citizens to central authority in exchange for political favor. In 1761, they were called Crown loyalists. They enforced the writs. They chose fidelity to power over fidelity to the people they governed.

Otis stood against them. The founders stood against them. The Revolution was fought against them.

Texas has chosen their side.

Not in name, no one swears allegiance to a king. But in function. In practice. In the quiet decision to serve the administration rather than protect the citizen. In the choice to comply when resistance was possible, legal, and right.

Twenty three states understood their duty. They are being sued for honoring it.

Texas understood something else: that loyalty to the powerful is easier than loyalty to principle. That compliance is safer than resistance. That the gap in the law is wide enough to walk through if you don't look back.

The Crown loyalists told themselves the same things.

Once DOJ holds this data, there is no meaningful limit on future use. It can be retained, cross referenced, and accessed by successor administrations with entirely different priorities.

Citizens know this.

And when citizens believe registering to vote places them in a federal database accessible without warrant or suspicion, some will not register. That is not speculation. It is how surveillance suppresses rights, quietly, indirectly, without a single law forbidding participation.

Texas didn't restrict voting outright. It made voting riskier.

Here is the standard Texas should have met:

When citizens provide sensitive information to exercise a constitutional right, the state owes them a fiduciary duty, to use the data only for its stated purpose and to refuse surrender absent due process.

Texas failed that test.

It surrendered the data voluntarily.

It provided no notice, no hearing, no opportunity to object.

It treated millions of citizens' personal information as a political asset.

The law may not yet punish this. That is an indictment of the law, not a defense of Texas.

Texas extended warrantless data access to a political ally and called it compliance. The Department of Justice demanded population wide personal data and called it enforcement.

Neither is telling the truth.

James Otis warned us 264 years ago. He called general warrants "the worst instrument of arbitrary power." He lost his case, the court upheld the writs. But he won the argument. The Revolution followed. The Fourth Amendment followed. The principle that government cannot seize the records of the citizenry without cause or oversight became foundational law.

Texas forgot that principle. Or worse, it remembered, and chose loyalty over liberty anyway.

The founders had a word for that choice. They called it Toryism. They fought a war to defeat it.

The law's silence does not absolve Texas.

Justice condemns it.

History already has a verdict.

And James Otis, who stood alone against lawful tyranny and called it what it was, would recognize exactly what happened here.

Authority without right is tyranny with paperwork.

Texas signed the paperwork.
